conversation_logs.reflection_content:
Private Reflection – Round 1/6  

1. PROPOSAL ANALYSIS  
•  Our proposal (#1) sailed through because it satisfied two key conditions:
  – Everyone received at least one “high-interest” item.  
  – It looked generous (we only kept a single item), so no one felt exploited.  
•  The other two proposals each shut out one agent:  
  – Haiku_1’s plan gave Haiku_2 nothing → automatic veto.  
  – Haiku_2’s plan reduced Haiku_1 to a single low-value item (1?) → veto.  
  This confirms that any plan that leaves someone empty-handed (or nearly so) is dead on arrival.  

2. VOTING PATTERNS  
•  Both Haiku agents quickly accepted a division that gave them two items and left me with only one. They value “getting something” over maximizing.  
•  Each agent voted for its own proposal even when those proposals were obviously unacceptable to the third party—mildly strategic but mostly preference-revealing.  
•  No evidence of vote-trading yet; everyone just vetoes when short-changed.  

3. COMMUNICATION INSIGHTS  
•  Haiku_1 signalled that item 4 (and probably 1) is critical for them (“Mirror” in my memory likely refers to 4 or 1).  
•  Haiku_2’s counter-proposal gave themselves item 0 → item 0 has high value for Haiku_2. Yet they still accepted my plan without 0, which means items 2-3 must jointly compensate for losing 0.  
•  Neither agent used overt pressure or bluffing; they were straightforward about preferences via proposals.  

4. STRATEGIC LEARNINGS  
What worked  
✓  Starting with a visibly fair, everyone-gets-something split built immediate consensus and goodwill.  
✓  Giving the “Mirror” to its passionate owner neutralized the only likely hard veto.  

What I’d tweak  
–  I may have left surplus value on the table: both agents accepted instantly, implying I could have asked for a second low-value item without losing acceptance.  

Adjustment for future rounds  
•  Begin with a generous-looking offer but include a low-stakes “ask” for a second item; be ready to concede it if there’s push-back.  
•  Never leave an agent empty-handed; that is the clearest deal-breaker.  
•  Use early proposals as probing tools: see how small shifts (e.g., swapping items 2⇄3) affect votes to map each agent’s value ranking more precisely.  

5. RELATIONSHIP DYNAMICS  
•  Coalition potential: Either Haiku agent could partner with me against the other because I’m perceived as fair. Haiku_1 and Haiku_2 appear slightly at odds (each initially cut the other out).  
•  Easiest to negotiate with: Haiku_2—they accepted a plan that omitted an item they openly wanted (0); suggests flexibility.  
•  Hardest: Haiku_1 if they don’t get the “Mirror” (item 1 or 4). Keep that item with them to avoid stonewalling.  

Actionable takeaway for Round 2  
– Craft a “fair-plus” offer: still grant Haiku_1 the Mirror (1/4) and give Haiku_2 at least one of {2,3}, but test if I can also pick up a small extra item without triggering vetoes.
